                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
                                        NZ to play  3 matches in Pakistan				   Wellington: New Zealand will play three limited-overs matches in Pakistan in the lead-up to September rsquo;s Champions Trophy tournament.   A New Zealand Cricket (NZC) spokesman said on Wednesday that dates and venues for the matches, likely to be played in the last week of August and the first week of September, would be confirmed when existing security concerns had been addressed. NZC spokesman Steve Addison said his organisation was working with New Zealand team members, their players rsquo; association, New Zealand rsquo;s Ministry of Foreign Affairs and other bodies to address security issues. Addison said no New Zealand player yet had made himself unavailable for the tour on security grounds.   NZ beat SA  Brisbane: New Zealand allrounder Jesse Ryder made a successful comeback from injury to lead New Zealand to a five-wicket win over South Africa in the Emerging Players cricket tournament on Tuesday. Ryder took two wickets as New Zealand bundled the Proteas out for just 94. He then opened the innings and scored 27 as New Zealand reached the winning total in the 28th over.  Candidates  Calcutta: Pradyut Bose and Arijit Roy were the new candidates for the vice-president rsquo;s posts in an otherwise unchanged panel named by the Prasun Mukherjee-led ruling group at the Cricket Association of Bengal on Wednesday, says A Staff Reporter. The annual general meeting is on July 29. Bose and Roy replaced Russi Jeejeebhoy and Nemai Dutta, whose terms have expired.   THE PANEL
  President: Prasun Mukherjee; Jt secretaries: Samar Paul and Amitava Banerjee; Treasurer: Tushar Sarkar; Vice-presidents: Indranath Dey, Subhashis Sarkar, Pradyut Bose and Arijit Roy.  Old name  Calcutta: Cricket Australia (CA) on Wednesday has announced that the historic Sheffield Shield will be returning as the Australian interstate first-class cricket trophy, says A Staff Reporter. According to a CA release, a five-year deal with Weet-Bix results in reinstatement of the Sheffield Shield, which was introduced in 1892-93 and was replaced with the Pura Cup in 1999-2000.  SLC move  Colombo: Sri Lankan Cricketers rsquo; (SLC) body on Wednesday said that the board was holding discussions with the ECB to reschedule the proposed England tour next year to accommodate its players for the Indian Premier League (IPL). Sri Lanka Cricketers rsquo; Association (SLCA) secretary Graeme Labrooy said SLC officials are exploring the possibility of rescheduling the matches in England next year to accommodate the players for IPL. 
                                                                                                                                                               
